Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide chips
(no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, sprinkle over the
@dried oregano{1%sachet}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread
out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

Meanwhile, trim the @baby gem lettuce{1}, halve lengthways, then thinly slice widthways.

Quarter the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g}. Cut the @feta cheese{50%g} into 1cm cubes.

In a large #bowl{}, combine the baby gem, tomato, feta, @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and
a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then set aside.

Break up the @unconventional plant-based burgers{2} into a medium bowl. Add the
@roasted spice and herb blend{1%sachet}, then mix together with your hands.

Shape into sausage shapes, 4 per person. Flatten to make koftas.

Pop the plant-based koftas onto another baking tray. Bake on the middle shelf of your
oven until browned, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Ensure they're piping hot throughout.

Meanwhile, in a small bowl, combine the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} and
@honey{15%g}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Spread the garlic over the @Greek style flatbreads{4}(2 per person) and drizzle with
the @olive oil{1%tbsp}.

Pop them onto the bottom shelf of your oven until warm and starting to turn golden,
~{3-4%minutes}.

When everything's ready, place the garlic flatbreads on each plate and top with a
handful of the Greek style salad, some chips and the plant-based koftas.

Serve the remaining salad and chips on the side.

Drizzle the honey yoghurt over the koftas to finish. Enjoy!